} Wait, the first number in each line is the cost (c[i][0]), then m numbers for the skills (c[i][1] to c[i][m]). Yes. Now, the loop over masks:

for (int mask=1; mask < (1<<n); mask++) {

    // process mask

} Now, the code for each mask as above. Putting it all together:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <limits.h>

#define MAX_N 20
#define MAX_M 20

int main() {
    int n, m, x; scanf("%d %d %d", &n, &m, &x);
    int c[MAX_N][MAX_M+1]; // columns 0 to m (m+1 columns)
    for (int i=0; i <n; i++) {
        for (int j=0; j <=m; j++) {
            scanf("%d", &c[i][j]);
        }
    }
    int min_cost = INT_MAX;
    for (int mask=1; mask < (1<<n); mask++) {
        int totals[m];
        int sum_cost =0;
        for (int s=0; s <m; s++) totals[s] =0;
        for (int i=0; i <n; i++) {
            if (mask & (1<<i)) {
                sum_cost += c[i][0];
                for (int s=1; s <=m; s++) {
                    totals[s-1] += c[i][s];
                }
            }
        }
        int valid =1;
        for (int s=0; s <m; s++) {
            if (totals[s] <x) {
                valid =0;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (valid) {
            if (sum_cost < min_cost) {
                min_cost = sum_cost;
            }
        }
    }
    if (min_cost == INT_MAX) {
        printf("-1\n");
    } else {
        printf("%d\n", min_cost);
    }
    return 0;
} Wait, but in the code above, the totals array is declared inside the mask loop, so it's reinitialized each time. This should work. Now, testing edge cases. Test case 1: n=1, m=1, x=5. Input:

1 1 5

10 5 

The subset is the only course. The skill sum is 5 which is equal to x. So the cost is 10. Output is 10. Another test case where no subset meets: 

n=1, m=1, x=6. The course has skill 5. Then output is -1. Another case with two courses:

